{{Div col end}}
Of the passengers, 42 boarded in [[Mumbai|Bombay]], including:<ref name="NYT"/>
* 3 Americans
* 19 Indians
* 9 [[Nigeria]]ns
* 9 [[Sri Lanka]]ns

The rest of the passengers boarded in Addis Ababa.

One hundred twenty-five of the 175 passengers and crew members were killed, as well as all three hijackers. Many of the passengers who died survived the initial crash, but they had disregarded or did not hear Leul's warning not to inflate their [[Personal flotation device|life jackets]] inside the aircraft, causing them to be pushed against the ceiling of the fuselage by the inflated life jackets when water flooded in. Unable to escape, they drowned. An estimated 60 to 80 passengers, strapped to their seats, presumably drowned.<ref>[http://www.cnn.com/WORLD/9611/23/hijack.ethiopia.update/index.html Ethiopian airline crash kills at least 50]. [[CNN]]. November 23, 1996.{{dead|date=August 2011}}</ref>

Leul and Yonas<!--Ethiopians do not have family names--> both survived. For his actions, Leul was awarded the Flight Safety Foundation Professionalism in Flight Safety Award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.flightsafety.org/aviation-awards/fsf-professionalism-award-flight-safety|title=Flight Safety Foundation Award in Flight Professionalism|date=|accessdate=2009-10-08|work=Flight Safety Foundation}}</ref>

===Notable passengers===
Among those killed was [[Mohamed Amin]], a famous wartime photojournalist and publisher of ''Selamta'', Ethiopian Airlines' in-flight magazine.<ref>Episode Seven, ''[[Mo & Me]]''</ref> He was believed to be standing near the entrance to the cockpit arguing and negotiating with the hijacker presumed to be guarding the cockpit during the final moments of the flight. Brian Tetley, Amin's colleague, also died.<ref>"[http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9906E7DC103DF935A15752C1A960958260 Mohamed Amin, 53, Camera Eye During the Famine in Ethiopia]," ''[[The New York Times]]''. November 26, 1996.</ref>

[[Franklin Huddle]], the U.S. Consul General of Bombay at the time, and his wife Chanya "Pom" Huddle both survived the crash.<ref name="FinishedLife"/> Huddle said that he chose to fly on Ethiopian Airlines while planning a [[safari]] trip to [[Kenya]] because of the airline's reputation. Huddle said in an interview that Ethiopian Airlines was one of two in Africa to have [[Federal Aviation Administration]] certification. Huddle wanted a flight during the day, reasoning that flying during the day was "safer."<ref name="AfricanHijack"/> Huddle credited his and his wife's survival to a last-minute upgrade to business class.<ref name="Brown">"[http://www.brownalumnimagazine.com/may/june-2002/no-resting-place.html No Resting Place]," ''[[Brown University]] Alumni Magazine''</ref>

Other passengers on the aircraft included Lt.Gen.(Ret.) [[Antal Annus]], the [[Hungary|Hungarian]] ambassador to Kenya,<ref name="Sinking"/> who died, and a [[France|French]] foreign ministry official.<ref>"[http://web.archive.org/web/20070205144457/http://www.cnn.com/WORLD/9611/24/ethiopia.hijack/index.html Bizarre ordeal recounted in Ethiopian Airlines crash]." ''[[CNN]]''. November 24, 1996. Retrieved on December 29, 2008.{{Dead link|date=May 2011}}</ref>

==Aftermath==
The incident has become a well-known hijacking because of the videotape.<ref name="Honeymooners"/> The video later served as an important tool in studies of aviation crashes and procedures.{{Citation needed|date=January 2010}}

This was one of very few large airliner [[water landing]]s, the first hijacked water landing. Both the captain and co-pilot of the flight received aviation awards, and both continued to fly for Ethiopian Airlines.<ref name="AfricanHijack"/>

==In the media==
The crash was featured in [[List of Mayday episodes#Season 3|two episodes]] of ''[[Mayday (TV series)|Mayday]]'' (''Air Emergency'', ''Air Crash Investigation''). One appeared in season 1 to explain what might have happened if [[Air Transat Flight 236]] had ditched instead of landing in a nearby airport. It appeared again in season 3, this time directly explaining the events of Flight 961. It was also featured in a 2010 episode of the [[Biography Channel]] series ''[[I Survived...]]'', in which a survivor told his story of what happened on the plane,<ref name="I Survived">[http://www.biography.com/listings/episode_details.do?episodeid=531484&airingid=17186298]</ref> and also appeared in the documentary ''Out of the Wreckage - Plane Crash Survivors'', which features crashes that were caught on camera and with survivors.{{Citation needed|date=June 2011}}

